Solution — Exercise 04: Valgrind Memory Leak
=============================================

Step 1: Run with Valgrind
  valgrind --leak-check=full --track-origins=yes ./target

Step 2: Read the output
  Valgrind will report something like:

  6 bytes in 1 blocks are definitely lost
    at malloc (vg_replace_malloc.c:...)
    by create_message (target.c:10)
    by main (target.c:18)        ← char *b = create_message("world")

  7 bytes in 1 blocks are definitely lost
    at malloc (vg_replace_malloc.c:...)
    by create_message (target.c:10)
    by main (target.c:19)        ← char *c = create_message("horizon")

  LEAK SUMMARY:
    definitely lost: 13 bytes in 2 blocks

Answers:
  - Bytes leaked: 13 (6 for "world" + 7 for "horizon")
  - Allocations leaked: 2
  - Lines: 18 and 19 in main (b and c are never freed)

The fix:
  free(b);
  free(c);

Why it matters:
  Memory leaks are invisible at runtime — the program appears correct.
  In long-running processes, leaked memory accumulates until the system
  runs out. Valgrind makes the invisible visible.

Step 3: Find the flag with GDB
  The flag lives in the leaked 'flag' pointer inside main().
  gdb ./target
  (gdb) break main
  (gdb) run
  (gdb) next    (repeat until past 'char *flag = create_message(...)')
  (gdb) print flag
  → $1 = 0x... "HRZ{leak_found}"

  Submit it: horizon done HRZ{leak_found}
